#. §2: `r`
#. §3: `lemma`
#. §4: `rw [lemma]`
#. §5: `l`
#. §6: `r`
#. §7: `r`
#. §8: `l`
#. §9: `rw [← lemma]`
#. §10: `rw [lemma] at h`
#. §11: `l`
#. §12: `h`
#. §13: `r`
#. §14: `Rewrite`
#. §15: `rw`
#. §16: `rfl`
#. §17: `lemma`
#. §18: `a`
#. §19: `a`
#. §20: `rw [lemma b]`
#. §21: `b`
#. §22: `lemma`
#. §23: `rw [lemma a b c ...]`
#. §24: `lemma`
#. §25: `rw [lemma1, lemma2, ...]`
#: Game.Metadata
msgid "§0 stands for rewrite. Let §1 and §2 be the left and right hand sides of some §3, then §4 replaces every instance of §5 in the goal with §6. If the goal instead has §7s that we want to replace with §8, we can do §9 (the arrow is typed using \\\\l). We can also do §10 to replace every instance of §11 in the hypothesis §12 with §13. There actually is a tactic called §14, but the difference is that §15 inherently attemps to use §16 at the end, which saves a line of proof and renders the former tactic obsolete. If §17's hypothesis includes a variable §18, then instead of letting Lean try and choose the first valid §19 in the proof, we can specify it ourselves using §20, where §21 is the variable we wanted to match. If §22 has multiple variables, we can specify all of them sequentially using §23. Similarly, if we have multiple §24s we want to replace, we can use §25."
msgstr ""

